    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>Hi everyone! I’m excited to share that I’ve created my own website today! Welcome to my blog!</p><p>In this post, I’ll share my step-by-step approach to using Hexo and GitHub to build it. </p><h3 id="Getting-Started"><a href="#Getting-Started" class="headerlink" title="Getting Started"></a>Getting Started</h3><p>Firstly, let’s talk about why I chose Hexo and GitHub for creating my website.</p><figure class="highlight python"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre><span class="line">1</span><br></pre></td><td class="code"><pre><code class="hljs python"><span class="hljs-built_in">print</span>(<span class="hljs-string">&quot;Hi, world!&quot;</span>)<br></code></pre></td></tr></table></figure><p><img src="/images/test.jpg" alt="image1"></p><h3 id="Setting-Up-Hexo"><a href="#Setting-Up-Hexo" class="headerlink" title="Setting Up Hexo"></a>Setting Up Hexo</h3><p>I started by installing Hexo and setting up the basic configuration…</p><h3 id="Using-GitHub-for-Deployment"><a href="#Using-GitHub-for-Deployment" class="headerlink" title="Using GitHub for Deployment"></a>Using GitHub for Deployment</h3><p>After setting up my website locally, I deployed it using GitHub Pages…</p><h3 id="Conclusion"><a href="#Conclusion" class="headerlink" title="Conclusion"></a>Conclusion</h3><p>Creating my own website has been an amazing journey…</p><p>I hope this guide helps you in your own website-building adventures!</p><p>Stay tuned for more updates and tips! Feel free to explore around and leave your comments below.</p><p>Happy website building!</p>]]></content>
    
    
    
